@article{Jiang2014,
annote = {From Duplicate 2 (Recovery of the static gravity field with Inclined Pendulum Formation - Jiang, Weiping; Liu, Wei; Xu, Xinyu; Zou, Xiancai; Zhao, Qian)

From Duplicate 2 (Recovery of the static gravity field with Inclined Pendulum Formation - Jiang, Weiping; Liu, Wei; Xu, Xinyu; Zou, Xiancai; Zhao, Qian)

Summary



The article describes the numerical experiments of a number of pendulum formations with the purpose of retrieving the gravity field. The pendulum formations is described by two parameters, the initial inclined angle (which is the azimuth angle of the inter-satellite vector) and the initial inter-satellite range (which is the distance between the satellites). Both parameters are defined only when the formation is crossing the equator.

A number of simulations is conducted for difference values of the two parameters (while the other parameters is kept constant at a pre-defined value). The simulations results are analysed in the frequency domain (with error amplitude per degree plots) and in the spatial domain (by the means of spatial maps).


General remarks

The article is generally poorly written, occasionally showing that little review was done by the authors. There are some sentences which are difficult to understand and are grammatically incorrect. Many terms are introduced without proper explanation.

The authors have reached a few interesting conclusions: they have shown that the East-West sensitivity of the ll-sst data contributes more significantly to estimate the (near) sectorial coefficients and that the North-South data sensitivity helps to determine the zonal and tesseral coefficients. They have also found that, under the assumptions of the conducted study, a pendulum formation with an initial inclined angle within the range of 45 to 60 degrees produces the lowest error and most isotropic error pattern. These results should be understood in the context that the validity of the assumptions is not necessarily general enough (see below).



Major Issues



The purpose of the numerical experiment is not clear. The titles states that it is for the recovery of the static gravity field but this is never mentioned explicitly on the text. Furthermore, at line 12-13 of page 9, they clearly state “we want to obtain the monthly gravity field” and proceed to motivate the choice of orbital repeat period based on this.

The conducted research seems unfinished, with the research skipping important details, such as: i) the simulation of time-varying gravity field, ii) the over-simplistic noise model (which considers only white noise and a limited number of error sources, when e.g. Ditmar 2012 has shown that the errors in GRACE data are coloured and of numerous types), and iii) the small maximum degree considered in the estimation of the error models. These issues make the conclusions drawn from the numerical study weaker since they are not general enough.

The simulation of temporal aliasing is avoided by retrieving the static gravity field. I'm afraid this is a very bad motivation to look at the static gravity field retrieval with ll-sst data. The GRACE/GOCE satellites have advanced the knowledge of the static gravity field considerably, much more than what is conceivably achievable with ll-sst data alone. As a result, the only valuable application for ll-sst data is to measure the time-variable gravity field. Unless the authors are able to show that the mission they propose can compete with the GRACE/GOCE data (maybe at degrees below 100, where the contribution of the GOCE data is not as high as that of GRACE), I strongly suggest they consider the temporal component of the gravity field.

The choice of maximum degree of the estimated gravity field error models is badly motivated. The authors say that “it is enough to show the error pattern of the IPF”. The error pattern at low degrees (below degree 60) is not necessarily representative of the error pattern at high degrees (above degree 100). Furthermore, independently of the aim of the paper, i.e. to study the retrieval of static or time-varying gravity field estimation (which is not clear), degree 60 is surely much too low. The time varying gravity field is routinely estimated from GRACE data up to degree 120 and satellite-only static gravity field solutions (which use, amongst others, GOCE data) go up to degree 250. Unless the authors can prove that the proposed IPF improves in particular the solution up to degree 60 relatively to existing real data solutions, there is little point in restricting the simulation to that degree.

There is a major drawback of the IPF as defined in the paper (i.e. with only difference on the longitude of the ascending node): the satellites are at minimum distance consistently at the poles, which means that the data at the polar areas is always of lower quality (because data collected with small inter satellite distance is less sensitive to long wavelength features of the gravity field). This deficiency of the simulated pendulum formations should be addressed by the authors, otherwise they risk reporting overly conservative results. By adding a small difference in orbital inclination between the orbits of the two satellites, the cross-over point (when the satellites are closest to each other) is shifted to a lower latitude. This point moves over different geographical locations (at the same latitude) as the Earth rotates in inertial space.


