@inproceedings{Forste2012,
abstract = {GFZ Potsdam and GRGS Toulouse have a long-time close cooperation in the field of global gravity field determination at which the present focus is (1) on GOCE gravity field determination and (2) on computation of combined gravity field models. The goal of GOCE is to map the gravity field of the Earth at a spatial resolution of about 100 km (i.e. spherical harmonics to degree and order 200) with an accumulated geoid error of less than 2-3 cm at this scale. We apply the direct numerical approach to compute GOCE gravity fields. This comprises (1) the estimation of the long wavelength gravity field signal from a dynamic orbit computation using precise kinematic orbit positions as observations (pseudo-SST) and (2) the discovery of the short wavelength information by analyzing the satellite gravity gradients (SGG). The 3-axes GOCE-gradiometer provides gravity gradients which are measurable with a high precision only within the measurement bandwidth (mbw) of approximately 0.005 to 0.1 Hz. This requires appropriate filtering of the gravity gradients and the associated observation equations. For this purpose we use an order 12 10-125 mHz band-pass filter. The pseudo-SST and the SGG measurements are processed separately, producing SST and high-resolution SGG normal equations. These matrices are subsequently combined and solved using Cholesky decomposition. Due to the polar gaps in the GOCE data, we apply the spherical cap regularization. In preparation of the fourth gravity field model that will be delivered to the scientific community in February 2013, we have computed a set of new GOCE gravity field models using the reprocessed gravity gradients provided by GOCE-HPF including the test-wise application of different band-pass filters We included the GOCE data in the combination of satellite and ground-based gravity data to obtain high-resolution global gravity field models. The first combined model containing GOCE data is our initial release of EIGEN-6, the latest combined EIGEN-model (EIGEN = European Improved Gravity model of the Earth by New techniques), published in 2011. It was computed from a combination of LAGEOS, GRACE and GOCE data, augmented with the DTU10 surface gravity data and is complete to degree and order 1440 (corresponding to 14 km spatial resolution). Now we present our new release of EIGEN-6 which is complete to degree and order 1990 (corresponding to 10 km spatial resolution). Furthermore this new model comprises extended measurement time spans for the LAGEOS/GRACE data as well as for the GOCE data. The comparison of test results (orbit computation, GPS leveling) of this latest EIGEN model with GOCE-only models, EGM2008 and ITG10S demonstrates the gain in accuracy at high degrees, while its performance is identical to a GRACE-only model for the low degrees. Compared to the first release of EIGEN-6 this new release shows a general improvement. Oceanographic validation of the new EIGEN-model in comparison to other global gravity field models is performed through the analysis of differences between mean geostrophic currents derived from the tested gravity field models and inferred from drifter data as a function of resolution (down to 100 km). The GOCE processing within this work was done in the framework of the European GOCE Gravity Consortium (EGG-C) under ESA contract within the ESA GOCE High Level Processing Facility (GOCE-HPF).},
